5. Key Methodological Notes

### RQ2 — Why `pd.qcut` Failed and the Corrected Approach

The initial tier assignment used `pd.qcut(x, q=3)` to divide Unit Price into Low / Mid / High thirds. This failed because:

- Unit Price is **discrete**, not continuous — each product has only 2–4 fixed SKU prices
- One SKU typically holds ~50% of orders, so the 33rd and 67th percentile cut points land on the **same value**
- This creates duplicate bin edges → `ValueError` → fallback assigns **all rows to "Mid"** → p-values of 1.000

Corrected method: SKU prices are ranked within each product category and assigned tiers directly:

| Product | Low | Mid | High |
|---|---|---|---|
| Smartphone | $20.75 | $791.19 | $1,139.68 |
| Laptop | $463.96 | — | $674.32 |
| Smartwatch | $459.50 | — | $844.83 |
| Tablet | $247.03 | — | $786.41 |
| Headphones | $361.18 | — | — |

Four single-order anomaly SKUs are excluded from analysis.

### Age Group Boundaries

| Group | Age Range | n |
|---|---|---|
| 18–30 | Young adults | 4,068 |
| 31–45 | Early mid-life | 4,872 |
| 46–60 | Mid-life | 4,726 |
| 61–80 | Older adults | 6,333 |

Boundaries are informed by the dataset's quartile structure (Q1 = 33, Q3 = 65).



6. Summary of Statistical Results

 RQ1 — Behavioural Indicators

| Indicator | Gender p | Age p | Significant? |
|---|---|---|---|
| Loyalty Conversion | 0.654 | 0.219 | No |
| Order Cancellation | 0.171 | 0.428 | No |
| Credit Card Usage | 0.658 | 0.726 | No |
| Shipping Type | 0.503 | 0.847 | No |

 RQ2 — Price Tier Preference

| Product | Gender p (χ²) | Age p (χ²) | Age p (ANOVA) |
|---|---|---|---|
| Smartphone | 0.537 | 0.761 | 0.366 |
| Laptop | 0.212 | 0.490 | 0.539 |
| Smartwatch | 0.512 | 0.338 | 0.339 |
| Tablet | 0.599 | 0.385 | 0.385 |

All Cohen's w and η² effect sizes < 0.03 (negligible).

 RQ3 — Revenue Drivers

| Driver | Pearson r with Total Price |
|---|---|
| Unit Price | 0.674 |
| Quantity | 0.654 |
| Add-on Total | ~0.12 (2% of revenue) |

Add-on finding: Attach rate is uniform across price levels (~75%), but customers buying premium SKUs spend ~2× more on add-ons ($83 vs $41). This is statistically significant for Smartphone and Laptop (both p < 0.001).

